{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775841847437,"sessionID":"ses_287965c48ffeBA0bj1XqfDCEYv","part":{"id":"prt_d786c27bc001uczm4yPt6iImVG","messageID":"msg_d786a7c52001tUODguZdFSf5Fk","sessionID":"ses_287965c48ffeBA0bj1XqfDCEYv","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-c3d0d575269f4791943853ce08e99726","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/delta-spec.md","content":"# AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP 服务框架\n\nModule: `pkg/workloadmanager`  \nLanguage: Go  \nSize: M\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nDefine the HTTP service framework for WorkloadManager, providing RESTful API infrastructure, middleware architecture, lifecycle management, health endpoints, and unified error handling.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### REQ-001: HTTPServer Configuration\n\n**GIVEN** the `server.go` file defines the HTTP server core implementation  \n**WHEN** a developer needs to configure and manage the HTTP server lifecycle  \n**THEN** `HTTPServer` struct and `Config` struct shall be available with proper fields and methods\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: HTTPServer struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\nWHEN reading the HTTPServer struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain fields: server *http.Server, router chi.Router, config Config, handlers map[string]Handler, logger Logger, stopCh chan struct{}\n\n// Scenario 2: Config struct fields\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/config.go\nWHEN reading the Config struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain fields: Addr string, ReadTimeout time.Duration, WriteTimeout time.Duration, IdleTimeout time.Duration, ShutdownTimeout time.Duration, EnableHealthz bool, EnableReadyz bool\n\n// Scenario 3: DefaultConfig function\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/config.go\nWHEN calling DefaultConfig()\nTHEN it SHALL return Config with Addr \":8080\", ReadTimeout 15s, WriteTimeout 15s, IdleTimeout 60s, ShutdownTimeout 30s, EnableHealthz true, EnableReadyz true\n\n// Scenario 4: HTTPServer constructor\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\nWHEN calling NewHTTPServer(cfg Config, logger Logger)\nTHEN it SHALL return *HTTPServer with router initialized using chi.NewRouter()\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-002: HTTPServer Lifecycle Management\n\n**GIVEN** HTTPServer needs to support graceful startup and shutdown  \n**WHEN** managing the server lifecycle  \n**THEN** Start, Stop, and GracefulShutdown methods shall be properly implemented\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: HTTPServer.Start method\nGIVEN an HTTPServer instance with valid config\nWHEN calling Start()\nTHEN it SHALL configure http.Server with timeouts from Config\nAND it SHALL start ListenAndServe on the configured address\nAND it SHALL return error channel for async error handling\n\n// Scenario 2: HTTPServer.Stop method\nGIVEN a running HTTPServer instance\nWHEN calling Stop(ctx context.Context)\nTHEN it SHALL call http.Server.Shutdown(ctx)\nAND it SHALL wait for existing connections to complete within ShutdownTimeout\nAND it SHALL close stopCh to signal shutdown complete\n\n// Scenario 3: HTTPServer.GracefulShutdown method\nGIVEN a running HTTPServer instance\nWHEN calling GracefulShutdown()\nTHEN it SHALL setup signal handler for SIGTERM and SIGINT\nAND it SHALL call Stop() on signal receipt\n\n// Scenario 4: Graceful shutdown with context timeout\nGIVEN an HTTPServer with ShutdownTimeout 30s\nWHEN graceful shutdown is triggered\nTHEN existing connections SHALL complete within 30 seconds\nAND new connections SHALL be rejected after shutdown starts\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-003: Router Implementation\n\n**GIVEN** the router needs to support route grouping and middleware scoping  \n**WHEN** configuring RESTful API routes  \n**THEN** Router struct wrapping chi.Router shall be properly defined\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: Router struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/router.go\nWHEN reading the Router struct\nTHEN it SHALL embed chi.Router\n\n// Scenario 2: NewRouter constructor\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/router.go\nWHEN calling NewRouter()\nTHEN it SHALL return *Router with chi.NewRouter() initialized\n\n// Scenario 3: RegisterHandlers method\nGIVEN a Router instance and multiple Handler implementations\nWHEN calling RegisterHandlers(handlers ...Handler)\nTHEN each handler's Register method SHALL be called on the underlying chi.Router\n\n// Scenario 4: chi router dependency\nGIVEN go.mod\nWHEN reading dependencies\nTHEN github.com/go-chi/chi/v5 SHALL be listed as a dependency\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-004: Handler Interface\n\n**GIVEN** handlers need a common registration interface  \n**WHEN** implementing new API endpoint handlers  \n**THEN** Handler interface and HandlerFunc type shall be properly defined\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: Handler interface definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/handler.go\nWHEN reading the Handler interface\nTHEN it SHALL define Register(r chi.Router) method\n\n// Scenario 2: HandlerFunc type definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/handler.go\nWHEN reading the HandlerFunc type\nTHEN it SHALL be defined as type HandlerFunc func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) error\n\n// Scenario 3: HandlerFunc.ServeHTTP implementation\nGIVEN a HandlerFunc instance\nWHEN calling ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request)\nTHEN it SHALL call the HandlerFunc and handle errors via HandleError\n\n// Scenario 4: RegisterHandler method on HTTPServer\nGIVEN an HTTPServer instance\nWHEN calling RegisterHandler(name string, h Handler)\nTHEN the handler SHALL be stored in handlers map\nAND it SHALL be registered on the router\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-005: Health Handler Implementation\n\n**GIVEN** Kubernetes needs liveness and readiness probe endpoints  \n**WHEN** implementing health check endpoints  \n**THEN** HealthHandler with /healthz and /readyz shall be properly implemented\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: HealthHandler struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go\nWHEN reading the HealthHandler struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain checker HealthChecker field\n\n// Scenario 2: HealthChecker interface definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go\nWHEN reading the HealthChecker interface\nTHEN it SHALL define IsHealthy() bool and IsReady() bool methods\n\n// Scenario 3: NewHealthHandler constructor\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go\nWHEN calling NewHealthHandler(checker HealthChecker)\nTHEN it SHALL return *HealthHandler with checker field set\n\n// Scenario 4: healthz endpoint\nGIVEN a HealthHandler registered on router\nWHEN GET request is sent to /healthz\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with JSON body {\"status\": \"ok\"}\n\n// Scenario 5: readyz endpoint with checker ready\nGIVEN a HealthHandler with checker where IsReady() returns true\nWHEN GET request is sent to /readyz\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with JSON body {\"status\": \"ready\"}\n\n// Scenario 6: readyz endpoint with checker not ready\nGIVEN a HealthHandler with checker where IsReady() returns false\nWHEN GET request is sent to /readyz\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 503 with JSON body {\"status\": \"not ready\"}\n\n// Scenario 7: readyz endpoint without checker\nGIVEN a HealthHandler with nil checker\nWHEN GET request is sent to /readyz\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 503 with JSON body {\"status\": \"not ready\"}\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-006: Logging Middleware\n\n**GIVEN** requests need structured logging  \n**WHEN** implementing request logging middleware  \n**THEN** LoggingMiddleware shall capture request details and response status\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: LoggingMiddleware struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\nWHEN reading the LoggingMiddleware struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain logger Logger field\n\n// Scenario 2: NewLoggingMiddleware constructor\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\nWHEN calling NewLoggingMiddleware(logger Logger)\nTHEN it SHALL return *LoggingMiddleware with logger field set\n\n// Scenario 3: Wrap method signature\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\nWHEN reading the Wrap method\nTHEN it SHALL have signature func(m *LoggingMiddleware) Wrap(next http.Handler) http.Handler\n\n// Scenario 4: Request logging fields\nGIVEN LoggingMiddleware wrapping a handler\nWHEN a request is processed\nTHEN logger SHALL log: method, path, status, duration\n\n// Scenario 5: responseWriterWrapper captures status\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\nWHEN reading responseWriterWrapper struct\nTHEN it SHALL embed http.ResponseWriter and capture status code field\n\n// Scenario 6: responseWriterWrapper.WriteHeader\nGIVEN a responseWriterWrapper instance\nWHEN WriteHeader(code int) is called\nTHEN status field SHALL be set to code\nAND embedded ResponseWriter.WriteHeader SHALL be called\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-007: Recovery Middleware\n\n**GIVEN** panics in handlers need to be recovered  \n**WHEN** implementing panic recovery middleware  \n**THEN** RecoveryMiddleware shall catch panics and return 500 response\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: RecoveryMiddleware struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery.go\nWHEN reading the RecoveryMiddleware struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain logger Logger field\n\n// Scenario 2: NewRecoveryMiddleware constructor\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery.go\nWHEN calling NewRecoveryMiddleware(logger Logger)\nTHEN it SHALL return *RecoveryMiddleware with logger field set\n\n// Scenario 3: Wrap method catches panic\nGIVEN RecoveryMiddleware wrapping a handler that panics\nWHEN the handler panics\nTHEN panic SHALL be recovered\nAND logger SHALL log error with panic value and path\nAND response SHALL be HTTP 500 with body \"Internal Server Error\"\n\n// Scenario 4: Normal request passes through\nGIVEN RecoveryMiddleware wrapping a normal handler\nWHEN the handler does not panic\nTHEN request SHALL pass through normally\nAND response SHALL be from the wrapped handler\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-008: CORS Middleware\n\n**GIVEN** cross-origin requests need CORS headers  \n**WHEN** implementing CORS middleware  \n**THEN** CORSMiddleware shall add appropriate CORS headers and handle preflight\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: CORSMiddleware struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors.go\nWHEN reading the CORSMiddleware struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain config fields for allowed origins, methods, headers\n\n// Scenario 2: CORS headers added to response\nGIVEN CORSMiddleware wrapping a handler\nWHEN a request is processed\nTHEN response SHALL include Access-Control-Allow-Origin header\n\n// Scenario 3: Preflight OPTIONS request\nGIVEN CORSMiddleware wrapping a handler\nWHEN OPTIONS request is sent\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with CORS preflight headers\nAND Access-Control-Allow-Methods header SHALL be present\nAND Access-Control-Allow-Headers header SHALL be present\n\n// Scenario 4: NewCORSMiddleware constructor\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors.go\nWHEN calling NewCORSMiddleware with allowed origins and methods\nTHEN it SHALL return *CORSMiddleware with config fields set\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-009: Request/Response Data Structures\n\n**GIVEN** API responses need unified JSON format  \n**WHEN** defining response data structures  \n**THEN** ErrorResponse and SuccessResponse shall be properly defined\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: ErrorResponse struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\nWHEN reading the ErrorResponse struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain fields: Code string with JSON tag \"code\", Message string with JSON tag \"message\", Details any with JSON tag \"details,omitempty\"\n\n// Scenario 2: SuccessResponse struct definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\nWHEN reading the SuccessResponse struct\nTHEN it SHALL contain field: Data any with JSON tag \"data\"\n\n// Scenario 3: ErrorResponse JSON serialization\nGIVEN an ErrorResponse with Code \"VALIDATION_ERROR\", Message \"Invalid parameter\", Details map[string]string{\"field\": \"name\"}\nWHEN marshaling to JSON\nTHEN output SHALL be {\"code\":\"VALIDATION_ERROR\",\"message\":\"Invalid parameter\",\"details\":{\"field\":\"name\"}}\n\n// Scenario 4: SuccessResponse JSON serialization\nGIVEN a SuccessResponse with Data containing a map\nWHEN marshaling to JSON\nTHEN output SHALL contain \"data\" key with the nested data\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-010: Unified Error Handling\n\n**GIVEN** errors need unified HTTP response format  \n**WHEN** handling errors in handlers  \n**THEN** HandleError function shall map errors to correct HTTP status codes and JSON responses\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: HandleError function signature\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\nWHEN reading HandleError function\nTHEN it SHALL have signature func HandleError(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request, err error)\n\n// Scenario 2: Validation error response\nGIVEN HandleError called with validation error\nWHEN the error indicates invalid request\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 400 with ErrorResponse Code \"VALIDATION_ERROR\"\n\n// Scenario 3: Not found error response\nGIVEN HandleError called with not found error\nWHEN the error indicates resource not found\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 404 with ErrorResponse Code \"NOT_FOUND\"\n\n// Scenario 4: Internal error response\nGIVEN HandleError called with internal error\nWHEN the error is unexpected\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 500 with ErrorResponse Code \"INTERNAL_ERROR\"\n\n// Scenario 5: Service unavailable error response\nGIVEN HandleError called with service unavailable error\nWHEN the error indicates dependency unavailable\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 503 with ErrorResponse Code \"SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE\"\n\n// Scenario 6: ErrorResponse sets Content-Type\nGIVEN HandleError writes ErrorResponse\nWHEN writing response\nTHEN Content-Type header SHALL be \"application/json\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-011: Middleware Chain Order\n\n**GIVEN** middleware needs to execute in correct order  \n**WHEN** configuring middleware on the router  \n**THEN** middleware shall execute in the order: Recovery → Logging → CORS → Handler\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: Recovery executes first\nGIVEN middleware chain Recovery → Logging → Handler that panics\nWHEN handler panics\nTHEN Recovery middleware SHALL catch panic before Logging logs\n\n// Scenario 2: Logging captures request duration\nGIVEN middleware chain Recovery → Logging → Handler\nWHEN request is processed\nTHEN Logging SHALL capture full request duration including handler execution\n\n// Scenario 3: Middleware setup method\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\nWHEN reading setupMiddleware method\nTHEN it SHALL apply middleware in correct order using chi.Use()\n\n// Scenario 4: CORS middleware optional\nGIVEN middleware configuration\nWHEN CORS middleware is not configured\nTHEN CORS middleware SHALL NOT be applied to the chain\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-012: Logger Interface\n\n**GIVEN** the server needs structured logging  \n**WHEN** defining logger abstraction  \n**THEN** Logger interface shall support Info and Error methods\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: Logger interface definition\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\nWHEN reading the Logger interface\nTHEN it SHALL define Info(msg string, args ...any) method\nAND it SHALL define Error(msg string, args ...any) method\n\n// Scenario 2: Logger usage in HTTPServer\nGIVEN an HTTPServer instance\nWHEN logging events\nTHEN logger.Info and logger.Error SHALL be used for structured logging\n\n// Scenario 3: Logger usage in middleware\nGIVEN LoggingMiddleware and RecoveryMiddleware\nWHEN logging request details or panics\nTHEN logger SHALL be used for all log output\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-013: Directory Structure\n\n**GIVEN** the module needs proper package structure  \n**WHEN** organizing code files  \n**THEN** files shall be organized according to the defined structure\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: Main package files\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\nWHEN listing files\nTHEN server.go, router.go, config.go, types.go SHALL exist\n\n// Scenario 2: Handlers directory\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/\nWHEN listing files\nTHEN handler.go and health.go SHALL exist\n\n// Scenario 3: Middleware directory\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/\nWHEN listing files\nTHEN logging.go, recovery.go, cors.go SHALL exist\n\n// Scenario 4: Package documentation\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/doc.go\nWHEN reading the file\nTHEN package-level godoc comment SHALL be present\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-014: Unit Tests\n\n**GIVEN** the implementation needs test coverage  \n**WHEN** verifying functionality  \n**THEN** unit tests shall cover all core components\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: Types tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN HandleError tests SHALL verify correct JSON format and status codes\nAND SuccessResponse tests SHALL verify correct marshaling\n\n// Scenario 2: Server tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN NewHTTPServer tests SHALL verify default config\nAND Start/Stop tests SHALL verify lifecycle\nAND graceful shutdown tests SHALL verify context timeout handling\n\n// Scenario 3: Router tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/router_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN NewRouter tests SHALL verify router initialization\nAND RegisterHandlers tests SHALL verify multiple handler registration\n\n// Scenario 4: Health handler tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN healthz test SHALL verify HTTP 200 with {\"status\": \"ok\"}\nAND readyz tests SHALL verify HTTP 200/503 based on IsReady()\n\n// Scenario 5: Logging middleware tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN tests SHALL verify request method, path, status captured\nAND responseWriterWrapper tests SHALL verify status code capture\n\n// Scenario 6: Recovery middleware tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN tests SHALL verify panic recovery\nAND tests SHALL verify HTTP 500 on panic\n\n// Scenario 7: CORS middleware tests\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors_test.go\nWHEN running tests\nTHEN tests SHALL verify Access-Control-Allow-Origin header\nAND tests SHALL verify OPTIONS preflight handling\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-015: Integration Tests\n\n**GIVEN** the server needs end-to-end verification  \n**WHEN** testing with real HTTP requests  \n**THEN** integration tests shall verify complete request flow\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: End-to-end health check\nGIVEN a running HTTPServer on random port\nWHEN GET request sent to /healthz\nTHEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with correct JSON body\n\n// Scenario 2: End-to-end readiness check\nGIVEN a running HTTPServer on random port\nWHEN GET request sent to /readyz\nTHEN response SHALL match HealthChecker state\n\n// Scenario 3: Middleware chain verification\nGIVEN a running HTTPServer with full middleware chain\nWHEN request is sent\nTHEN middleware SHALL execute in correct order\nAND logging SHALL capture request details\n\n// Scenario 4: Panic recovery in integration\nGIVEN a running HTTPServer with endpoint that panics\nWHEN request is sent to panicking endpoint\nTHEN server SHALL NOT crash\nAND response SHALL be HTTP 500\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-016: Code Quality\n\n**GIVEN** the code needs to meet quality standards  \n**WHEN** running linting and validation  \n**THEN** code shall pass go vet and golangci-lint\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```go\n// Scenario 1: go vet passes\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\nWHEN running go vet ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\nTHEN zero issues SHALL be reported\n\n// Scenario 2: golangci-lint passes\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\nWHEN running golangci-lint run ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\nTHEN zero linting issues SHALL be reported\n\n// Scenario 3: Build succeeds\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\nWHEN running go build ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\nTHEN build SHALL succeed without errors\n\n// Scenario 4: Test coverage threshold\nGIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\nWHEN running go test -cover ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\nTHEN coverage SHALL be greater than 80%\n```\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/server.go` | HTTPServer implementation with lifecycle management |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/router.go` | Router struct wrapping chi.Router |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/config.go` | Config struct and DefaultConfig function |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/types.go` | ErrorResponse, SuccessResponse, HandleError, Logger interface |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/doc.go` | Package-level documentation |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/handler.go` | Handler interface and HandlerFunc type |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go` | HealthHandler and HealthChecker interface |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go` | LoggingMiddleware and responseWriterWrapper |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery.go` | RecoveryMiddleware |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors.go` | CORSMiddleware |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/server_test.go` | HTTPServer unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/router_test.go` | Router unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/types_test.go` | Types and HandleError unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health_test.go` | HealthHandler unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging_test.go` | LoggingMiddleware unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery_test.go` | RecoveryMiddleware unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors_test.go` | CORSMiddleware unit tests |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/integration_test.go` | End-to-end integration tests |\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n| Package | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| `net/http` | Standard library HTTP server |\n| `context` | Request context for graceful shutdown |\n| `sync` | Concurrency control |\n| `os/signal` | Signal handling for graceful shutdown |\n| `time` | Timeout configuration |\n| `encoding/json` | JSON serialization for responses |\n| `github.com/go-chi/chi/v5` | Lightweight HTTP router |\n\n---\n\n## API Endpoints\n\n| Endpoint | Method | Purpose |\n|----------|--------|---------|\n| `/healthz` | GET | Kubernetes liveness probe |\n| `/readyz` | GET | Kubernetes readiness probe |\n\n---\n\n## Error Codes\n\n| Code | HTTP Status | Description |\n|------|-------------|-------------|\n| `VALIDATION_ERROR` | 400 | Invalid request parameter |\n| `NOT_FOUND` | 404 | Resource not found |\n| `INTERNAL_ERROR` | 500 | Unexpected server error |\n| `SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE` | 503 | Dependency unavailable |\n\n---\n\n## Validation Checklist\n\n- [ ] HTTPServer supports graceful startup and shutdown\n- [ ] Router framework supports route grouping with chi\n- [ ] Middleware chain executes in correct order\n- [ ] Health endpoints `/healthz` and `/readyz` respond correctly\n- [ ] Error responses use unified JSON format\n- [ ] Pass `go vet` with zero issues\n- [ ] Pass `golangci-lint` with zero issues\n- [ ] Unit tests pass with >80% coverage\n- [ ] Integration tests pass\n- [ ] All exported types have godoc comments"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1/types_test.go":[]},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/delta-spec.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775841847304,"end":1775841847434}}}}
